{{Main|Orange (color)}} [[Image:Orange by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|An orange light shows variations of the color orange.]] {{infobox color | title= Orange | pic = Image:Color icon orange v2.svg | wavelength=585â620 | hex= FF7F00 | r=255|g=127|b= 0 | c= 0|m= 50|y=100|k= 0 | h= 30|s=100|v=100 | spelling=Color | source=[http://tx4.us/moacolor.htm HTML Color Chart @30] }}
This article is a catalog of notable [[tints and shades]] of the [[color]] [[Orange (colour)|orange]].
Orange pigments are largely in the [[ochre]] or [[Cadmium pigments|cadmium]] families.
==Orange (color wheel)== {{-}} {{infobox color| title= Orange (color wheel)| hex= FF7F00| r=255|g=127|b= 0| c= 0|m= 50|y=100|k= 0| h= 30|s=100|v=100| spelling=Color| |source=[http://tx4.us/moacolor.htm HTML Color Chart @30] }} At right is the color '''orange''', also known as '''color wheel orange'''. This is the tone of orange that is a pure [[Colorfulness|chroma]] on the [[HSV color space|HSV color wheel]], the expression of which is known as the [[:File:RBG color wheel.svg|RGB color wheel]], exactly halfway between [[red]] and [[yellow]]. {{-}} ==Variations of orange== ===Papaya whip=== {{infobox color| title= Papaya Whip| hex= FFEFD5| r=255|g=239|b=213| c= |m= |y= |k= | h= 40|s= 97|v= 97 |source=[[Web colors#X11 color names|X11]]}}
Displayed at right is the [[web color]] '''papaya whip''', a pale [[tint]] of orange.
''Papaya whip'' is a representation of the color that would result if mashed [[papaya]]s were blended with [[vanilla]] [[ice cream]], [[whipped cream]], or [[yogurt]].{{cn|date=October 2011}}
{{-}}
===Melon=== [[File:Canteloupe and cross section.jpg|thumb|left|175px|A [[cantaloupe]] from Australia]] {{infobox color| title= Melon| hex= FDBCB4| r= 253|g=188|b=180| c= 0|m= 26|y= 91|k= 1| h= 7|s= 29|v= 99<ref> [http://web.forret.com/tools/color.asp?RGB=%23FDBCB4 web.forret.com Color Conversion Tool set to hex code of color #FDBCB4 (Melon):]</ref> |source=[[List of Crayola crayon colors#Standard Colors|Crayola]]}}
Displayed at right is the color '''melon'''.
This color is a representation of the color of the interior flesh of a [[cantaloupe]], the most commonly consumed [[melon]].
The first recorded use of ''melon'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1892.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 199; Color Sample of Melon: Page 27 Plate 2 Color Sample D10 </ref>
In 1949, "melon" was formulated as one of the [[Crayola]] colors.
{{-}}
===Atomic tangerine=== {{infobox color| title= Atomic Tangerine| hex= FF9966| r= 255|g=153|b=102| c= |m= |y= |k= | h= 20|s=100|v= 75 |source=[[List of Crayola crayon colors|Crayola]]}}
Displayed at right is the color '''atomic tangerine'''.
This color was formulated by [[Crayola]] in 1990.
{{-}}
===Tea rose=== {{infobox color|textcolor=black| title= Tea Rose (orange)| hex=F88379| r=248|g=131|b=121| |h=16|s= 70|v=70 |source=[http://tx4.us/nbs/nbs-t.htm ISCC-NBS]}} At right is displayed the color '''tea rose'''.
This color is the color of a type of orange rose called a ''tea rose''<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930--McGraw-Hill--Discussion of color Tea Rose, Page 183 </ref>.
The first recorded use of ''tea rose'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1884.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 183 </ref> The source of this color is the following website: [http://tx4.us/nbs/nbs-t.htm ISCC-NBS Dictionary of Color Names (1955)--Color Sample of Tea Rose (color sample #26)] {{-}} ===Carrot orange=== [[Image:CarrotRoots.jpg|175px|left|thumb|[[Carrot]]s]] {{infobox color| title=Carrot Orange| hex=ED9121| r=237|g=145|b=33| c=4|m=50|y=100|k=0| h=33|s= 86|v=93| |source=Maerz and Paul}}
'''Carrot orange''' is a tint of orange that is a representation of the color of the raw [[carrot]] vegetable.
The first recorded use of ''carrot orange'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1684.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 192; Color Sample: Carrot Orange Page 43 Plate 10 Color Sample C11</ref>
{{-}}
===Orange peel=== [[File:Orange and cross section.jpg|thumb|left|Orange fruit and cross section]] {{infobox color| title= Orange Peel| hex= FF9F00| r=255|g=159|b= 0| c= 0|m= 35|y=100|k= 0| h= 38|s=100|v=100| |source=Maerz and Paul}} Displayed at right is the color '''orange peel'''.
A discussion of the difference between the color ''[[orange (colour)|orange]]'' (the color halfway between red and yellow, shown below as ''color wheel orange'') and the color ''orange peel'' (the actual color of the outer skin of an orange), may be found in Maerz and Paul.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930--McGraw-Hill--Discussion of color Orange, Page 170</ref> "Orange peel" is the color halfway between [[Variations of orange#Orange (color wheel)|orange (color wheel)]] and [[Amber (color)|amber]] on the color wheel.
The first recorded use of ''orange peel'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1839.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 200; Colour Sample: Orange Peel Page 43 Plate 10 Color Sample L10.</ref> {{-}}
===Orange (web color)=== {{infobox color| title= Orange (web color)| hex= FFA500| r=255|g=165|b= 0| c= 0|m= 40|y=100|k= 0| h= 32|s=100|v=100| |source=[[Web colors#X11 color names|X11]]}} At right is the [[web color]] called '''orange'''. It is defined in [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]] as the [[Web color|hex triplet]] FFA500. {{-}} ===Dark orange (web color)=== {{infobox color| title=Dark Orange| hex=FF8C00| r=255|g=140|b=0| c=0|m=62|y=100|k=0| h=34|s=100|v=94| |source=[[Web colors#X11 color names|X11]]}}
The web color called '''dark orange''' is at the right. {{-}}
===Princeton orange=== {{infobox color| title= Princeton Orange|textcolor=black| hex= F46F1B| r=244|g=111|b= 27| c= 0|m= 44|y= 100|k= 0| h= 34|s=100|v= 100<ref> [http://web.forret.com/tools/color.asp?RGB=%23F46F1B web.forret.com Color Conversion Tool set to hex code of color #F46F1B (Princeton Orange):]</ref>| source=[[:File:Princeton shield.svg|Heraldic]]}}
The color '''Princeton orange''' is displayed at right.
This is the color that [[Symbol|symbolizes]] [[Princeton University]].
The first recorded use of ''Princeton orange'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1928.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 202; Color Sample of Princeton Orange: Page 41 Plate 9 Color Sample K11 </ref>
{{-}} ===Tangerine=== The first recorded use of ''tangerine'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1899.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 205; Color Sample: Tangerine Page 27 Plate 2 Color Sample H11</ref> {{-}} ===Pumpkin=== {{Anchor|Pumpkin}} [[Image:Pumpkins.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Cucurbita]] upon which the color "pumpkin" is based.]] '''Pumpkin''' is a color that resembles [[pumpkin]]s.
The first recorded use of ''pumpkin'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1922.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 202; Color Sample of Pumpkin: Page 43 Plate 10 Color Sample H11</ref>
Pumpkin or [[Orange (color)|orange]] is used with [[black]] for [[Halloween]] decorations. {{-}}
===Tomato=== {{anchor|Tomato}} {{infobox color| title= Tomato| hex= FF6347| r=255|g=99|b= 71| c= 0|m= |y= |k= 0| h= 15|s= 75|v=50 |source=[[Web colors#X11 color names|X11]]}}
The [[web color]] '''tomato''' is a medium [[red]]dish-[[Orange (color)|orange]] [[color]] that is the color of actual supermarket [[Tomato|tomatoes]]. Many vine-ripened tomatoes are a bit redder. The color of [[tomato soup]] is slightly less saturated. The color ''tomato'' is displayed at right.
[[Image:Tomato_soup.jpg|left|thumb|A bowl of tomato soup]]
The first recorded use of ''tomato'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1891.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 205; Color Sample of Tomato: Page 29 Plate 3 Color Sample I12</ref>
When the [[X11 color names]] were invented in the 1987, the color tomato was formulated as one of them. In the early 1990s, the X11 colors became known as the ''X11 [[web colors]]''. {{-}} ===Bittersweet=== {{infobox color| title= Bittersweet|textcolor=black| hex= FE6F5E| r=254|g=111|b= 94| c= 0|m= 56|y= 63|k= 0| h= 6|s= 63|v=100<ref> [http://web.forret.com/tools/color.asp?RGB=%23FE6F5E web.forret.com Color Conversion Tool set to hex code of color #FE6F5E (Bittersweet):]</ref>| source=[[List of Crayola crayon colors|Crayola]]}}
The color '''bittersweet''' is displayed at right.
The first recorded use of ''bittersweet'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in 1892.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 190; Color Sample of Bittersweet: Page 29 Plate 3 Color Sample J12 </ref>
In 1949, "bittersweet" was made into a [[Crayola]] color. {{-}} ===Alloy orange=== {{infobox color| title= Alloy Orange|textcolor=white| hex= C46210| r=196|g= 98|b= 16| c= 0|m= 50|y= 91|k= 23| h= 27|s= 92|v= 77<ref>[http://web.forret.com/tools/color.asp?RGB=%23C46210 web.forrett.com Color Conversion Tool set to hex code #C46210 (Alloy Orange):]</ref> |source=[[List of Crayola crayon colors#Metallic FX|Crayola]]}}
Displayed at right is the color '''alloy orange'''.
''Alloy orange'' is one of the colors in the special set of metallic [[Crayola]] crayons called [[List of Crayola crayon colors#Metallic FX|Metallic FX]], the colors of which were formulated by Crayola in 2001. {{-}} ===Burnt orange=== {{infobox color| title= Burnt Orange|textcolor=white| hex= CC5500| r=204|g= 85|b= 0| c= 0|m= 65|y=100|k= 9| h= 25|s=100|v= 80| source=[[University of Texas at Austin]]<ref name="burnt-orange">{{cite web|url=http://www.utexas.edu/visualguidelines/vg_colors.html |title=Visual Guidelines - Graphics - Colors |publisher=University of Texas at Austin |date=2007-06-06 |accessdate=2009-06-12}}</ref>}}
'''Burnt orange''' has been used as a color name for this medium dark shade of orange since 1915.<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York: 1930--McGraw-Hill (see under Burnt Orange in Index, Page 191)</ref> This color is one variation that is used as a school color of [[Auburn University]], [[Virginia Tech]], [[University of Texas at Austin]], [[Westwood High School (Austin, Texas)]], and [[Mesa_Verde_High_School|Mesa Verde High School (Citrus Heights, California)]]. The color was also used by the [[University of Montana]] prior to 1996 and Oklahoma State University for its football uniforms from 1973 through 1983. The NHL's [[San Jose Sharks]] also use burnt orange as a secondary color.
Burnt orange was popular in [[interior design]] in the 1970s. {{-}} ===Bittersweet shimmer=== {{infobox color| title= Bittersweet Shimmer|textcolor=white| hex= BF4F51| r=191|g= 79|b= 81| c= 0|m= 59|y= 58|k= 25| h=359|s= 59|v= 75<ref> [http://web.forret.com/tools/color.asp?RGB=%23BF4F51 web.forret.com Color Conversion Tool set to hex code of color #BF4F51 (Bittersweet Shimmer):]</ref>| source=[[List of Crayola crayon colors#Metallic FX|Crayola]]}}
Displayed at right is the color '''bittersweet shimmer'''.
''Bittersweet shimmer'' is one of the colors in the special set of metallic [[Crayola]] crayons called [[List of Crayola crayon colors#Metallic FX|Metallic FX]], the colors of which were formulated by Crayola in 2001. {{-}} ===Brown=== {{main|Brown}} '''Brown''' is actually derived from the orange part (orange + [[grey]]) of the color [[spectrum]]. It can be described as ''dark orange''. {{-}}
===Persian orange=== {{anchor|Persian orange}} {{infobox color| title= Persian Orange|textcolor=black| hex=D99058| r= 217|g= 144|b= 88| c= 0|m= 34|y= 59|k= 15| h= 26|s= 59|v= 85<ref>[http://web.forret.com/tools/color.asp?RGB=%23D99058 web.forrett.com Color Conversion Tool set to hex code #D99058 (Persian Orange) :] </ref> |source=[http://tx4.us/nbs/nbs-p.htm ISCC-NBS]}}
'''Persian orange''' is a [[color]] used in [[pottery]] and [[Persian carpet]]s in [[Iran]].
The first recorded use of ''Persian orange'' as a color name in [[English language|English]] was in [[1892]].<ref> Maerz and Paul ''A Dictionary of Color'' New York:1930 McGraw-Hill Page 201; color sample of Persian orange: Page 43 Plate 10 Color Sample F10</ref>
[[Orange (fruit)|Orange]] [[pudding]] (milk added to pureed oranges that is mixed in a blender with flour and slowly boiled on a stovetop) is colored Persian orange, assuming no [[food coloring]] is added. [[Allis-Chalmers]] tractors have been colored Persian orange since 1928 so that, even when caked with dirt, they could still be distinguished from landscape features.<ref>Now called "Persian Orange No. 1" (Guy Fay, Andy Kraushaar, ''Original Allis-Chalmers, 1933-1957'' 2000:121; [http://tractorman.20megsfree.com/about.html My Allis-Chalmers story]</ref>
